3. Underscores the need for a smooth transition from BINUB to BNUB;

4. Underlines the importance of establishing a fully integrated office with effective coordination among UN agencies, funds and programmes in Burundi;

5. Recognizes the primary responsibility of the Government of Burundi for peacebuilding, security and long-term development;

6. Encourages the Government to pursue efforts on peace consolidation, democratic governance, security sector reform, justice and human rights protection;

7. Encourages the Government to redouble efforts to pursue structural reforms aimed at improving governance and tackling corruption;

8. Urges international partners to support the Government's efforts to professionalize and enhance the capacity of national security services;

9. Commends the Government for completing the reintegration of children formerly associated with armed groups and ex-combatants;

10. Encourages the Government, the Peacebuilding Commission, and international partners to honour commitments under the Strategic Framework for Peacebuilding;

11. Urges the Government to investigate reports of human rights violations and prevent further violations;

12. Calls upon the Government to promote and protect human rights and establish the National Independent Human Rights Commission;

13. Welcomes the completion of national consultations on transitional justice mechanisms and encourages the Government to establish the proposed mechanisms;

14. Welcomes progress towards achieving durable solutions for refugees living in Tanzania;

15. Requests the Secretary-General to keep the Council informed on the implementation of BNUB's mandate and develop benchmarks for the future evolution of BNUB;

16. Decides to remain actively seized of the matter.
